land, United Kingdom","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gunner","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southeastern England, of Norman origin): from the Old Norse female personal name <i>Gunvor</i>, <i>Gunwǫr</i>, <i>Gunnor</i>, also a common Norman name, usually Latinized as <i>Gunnora</i>, composed of the elements <i>gunn</i> ‘battle’ + <i>vǫr</i>, a feminine form of <i>varr</i> ‘defender’.","English: occupational name for an operator of heavy artillery from Middle English <i>gonner</i> ‘gunner’.","Americanized form of German <b>Gönner</b>, a habitational name for someone from any of numerous places called Gönne."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":39,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":48,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":59,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William John Gunner was born in 1510, in Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. He died on 19 October 1592, in London, Middlesex, England, at the age of 82, and was buried in Middlesex, England."},"et":{"1510–19 October 1592":"1510–19. oktoober 1592","1510–Female":"1510–Surnud","1530–1592":"1530–1592","1510–1592":"1510–1592","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1510":"1510","19 October 1592":"19. oktoober 1592","1530":"1530","1592":"1592","1549":"1549","Buckinghamshire, Middlesex, London, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Buckinghamshire, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England"},"fi":{"1510–19 October 1592":"1510–19. lokakuuta 1592","1510–Female":"1510–Kuollut","1530–1592":"1530–1592","1510–1592":"1510–1592","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1510":"1510","19 October 1592":"19. lokakuuta 1592","15